    <div class="kicker">
      <time class="updated" datetime="2011-12-15T08:16:00+00:00">Thursday, December 15, 2011</time>
    </div>
    <h1 class="title" >
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2011/12/in-my-better-moments/">In my better moments</a>
    </h1>
  </header>
  <div class="post-content" itemprop="articleBody">
    <p>About three weeks ago, I printed out all the drafts Iâ€™ve written so far for <a href="http://orangette.blogspot.com/2011/04/its-still-at-it.html" target="_blank">my next book</a>, and then I spent three weeks avoiding reading them.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/e80a5-423300241.jpg"><img decoding="async" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/e80a5-423300241.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="1600" height="1061" border="0" /></a></p>
<p>I finally got up the courage on Sunday night. I poured myself a beer, sat down at the dining room table, and read through all of it. Afterward, I wanted to stab myself in the eye. But that didnâ€™t seem like it would make the manuscript any better, so I went to bed.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/2314d-488600091.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/2314d-488600091.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="1600" height="1090" border="0" /></a><br />
<a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/260ab-6513832243_f4710b8480_b1.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/260ab-6513832243_f4710b8480_b1.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="1024" height="679" border="0" /></a></p>
<p>I woke up at five the next morning. While I lay there in the dark, thinking about the injustice of being awake at such an hour on my day off, I remembered how rough and horrible my drafts were, and then I started thinking about that instead, and then I started sweating. I finally got out of bed at 6:45, put on my bathrobe, sat down at my desk, and started to write. My drafts are still rough and horrible, and they will be for a while, until I know what to do with them. But for as long as I sat at my desk, I felt better. When Iâ€™m writing, when my fingers are moving over the keys and words are marching across the screen, I donâ€™t worry. Physically, I canâ€™t worry; thereâ€™s no space for it in my head. I wish I could remember that more easily, so that I could choose to write first, rather than worry.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/22bb7-6322882935_be9b2a7b32_b1.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/22bb7-6322882935_be9b2a7b32_b1.jpg?w=199" alt="" width="679" height="1024" border="0" /></a></p>
<p>REMEMBER THAT, MOLLY.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/9534b-423300261.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/9534b-423300261.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="1600" height="1061" border="0" /></a></p>
<p>Then again, I wonâ€™t really have to remember, because Iâ€™ll be sitting at that desk for the majority of my waking hours between now and March 1, when my manuscript is due. Iâ€™m terrified. And, in my better moments, excited.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/e8a3f-104200361.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/e8a3f-104200361.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="1544" height="1024" border="0" /></a><br />
<a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/96ed4-488600341.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/96ed4-488600341.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="1600" height="1090" border="0" /></a></p>
<p>When Iâ€™m writing a lot, I like to read about writing. It makes me feel less crazy. Lately, Iâ€™ve been reading Stephen Kingâ€™s <span style="font-style: italic;"><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Writing-10th-Anniversary-Memoir-Craft/dp/1439156816?_encoding=UTF8&amp;tag=orangette-20&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;qid=1323937569&amp;camp=1789&amp;sr=8-1&amp;creative=9325" target="_blank">On Writing</a></span>, which I think one of you may have recommended to me? In any case, this passage on page 153 nails it.</p>
<p><span style="font-style: italic;">Once I start work on a project, I donâ€™t stop and I donâ€™t slow down unless I absolutely have to. If I donâ€™t write every day, the characters begin to stale off in my mind â€“ they begin to</span> seem <span style="font-style: italic;">like characters instead of real people. The taleâ€™s narrative cutting edge starts to rust and I begin to lose my hold on the storyâ€™s plot and pace. Worst of all, the excitement of spinning something new begins to fade. The work starts to </span>feel <span style="font-style: italic;">like work, and for most writers that is the smooch of death. . . . </span></p>
<p><span style="font-style: italic;">I used to tell interviewers that I wrote every day except for Christmas, the Fourth of July, and my birthday. That was a lie. I told them that because if you agree to an interview you have to say </span>something<span style="font-style: italic;">, and it plays better if itâ€™s something at least half-clever. Also, I didnâ€™t want to sound like a workaholic dweeb (just a workaholic, I guess). The truth is that when Iâ€™m writing, I write every day, workaholic dweeb or not. That</span> includes <span style="font-style: italic;">Christmas, the Fourth, and my birthday (at my age you try to ignore your goddam birthday anyway). And when Iâ€™m not working, Iâ€™m not working at all, although during those periods of full stop I usually feel at loose ends with myself and have trouble sleeping. For me, not working is the real work</span>.</p>
<p><a href="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/6719e-104400121.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/6719e-104400121.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="1544" height="1024" border="0" /></a></p>
<p>Hi from here.</p>
  </div>
