  <li id="comment-36187" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/03091737225622505900" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Jennifer</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2011/12/in-my-better-moments/#comment-36187"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2011-12-16T14:35:14-05:00">Friday, December 16, 2011 at 2:35 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hi Molly, Next time you&#39;re inclined to pick up a writing book, consider <i>The Tao of Writing: Imagine. Create. Flow.</i> by Ralph Wahlstrom. When I was teaching a graduate-level writing course, I must have read 30 books about writing and it was the one I chose for my students. It taught me how to ensure I didn&#39;t try to do too much or too little in my writing. Good luck and thanks for sharing with us.</p>
    </div>

